
    Matthew Hedges: Academic 'psychologically tortured' in UAE jail

        

    
        
                
                Image copyright
                 Daniela Tejada
                
            
            
            Image caption
                
                    Daniela Tejada helped secure her husband's release
                
            The British academic jailed for spying in the United Arab Emirates (UAE) has told how he endured "psychological torture".Matthew Hedges, 31, said he was forced by the Emirati authorities to stand "all day" in ankle cuffs.Mr Hedges said he suffered panic attacks and had suicidal thoughts.He told the BBC he was asked to act as a double agent in the UK's Foreign Office, and confessed to being a captain in MI6 to stop the "torture". Mr Hedges had denied spying and said he had been researching his PhD, but was jailed for life last month after a five-minute trial. 
    
        
The UAE government said the Durham academic was "100% a spy", but pardoned him on 26 November.
    
        
