                 EPA/DANIELA TEJADA
                
            
            
            Image caption
                
                    Matthew Hedges has always maintained his innocence and said he had been researching his PhD
                
            He said he was only able to speak to his wife Daniela Tejada - who had been campaigning for his release - once a week. During hours of interrogations he said the psychological pressure was so great he confessed."I panicked and told them I was a captain in MI6 - I told them what they wanted to hear."He also spoke of how he felt when he was sentenced to life in prison. 'Think twice'"It was total shock - I wasn't able to process it. I couldn't say goodbye to Danni."Ms Tejada said academics would now have to think twice before doing research in the UAE.She said: "At the heart of it it's about drawing red lines. I think the biggest issue is naturally the fact that there is no academic freedom in the UAE but also the fact that the red lines aren't clearly drawn. "So it's sort of every man on their own. Each academic will have a different experience - to assess how safe it is to do research." 
            

